$eduLessons = [
  [1, 'The Laws of the Game', 'both', '20 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-book-fill',
   "Understanding the 17 Laws of Football is essential for every player and coach.\n\n**The 17 Laws:**\n1. The Field of Play — dimensions, markings, goals\n2. The Ball — size, weight, pressure\n3. The Players — 11 per team, goalkeeper rules\n4. The Players' Equipment — boots, shin guards, no jewellery\n5. The Referee — authority, decisions are final\n6. The Other Match Officials — assistant referees, VAR\n7. The Duration of the Match — 90 minutes, two halves\n8. The Start and Restart of Play — kick-off, dropped ball\n9. The Ball In and Out of Play — when play stops\n10. Determining the Outcome — goals, extra time, penalties\n11. Offside — position, involvement in play\n12. Fouls and Misconduct — direct/indirect free kicks, cards\n13. Free Kicks — direct vs indirect\n14. The Penalty Kick — spot, run-up, goalkeeper position\n15. The Throw-In — technique, position\n16. The Goal Kick — from goal area\n17. The Corner Kick — from corner arc\n\n**Key Rule for Players:** You are offside if you are nearer to the opponent's goal line than both the ball and the second-last opponent when the ball is played to you.\n\n**Key Rule for Coaches:** Understanding Laws 12 (Fouls) and 11 (Offside) helps you design training that avoids unnecessary stoppages and exploits tactical advantages."],

  [2, 'Football Ethics & Fair Play', 'both', '15 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-shield-check',
   "Football is more than a game — it is a platform for character development.\n\n**Core Principles of Fair Play:**\n- **Respect** — for opponents, referees, teammates, and the game itself\n- **Integrity** — playing honestly, no diving, no time-wasting\n- **Inclusion** — welcoming players of all backgrounds, abilities, and genders\n- **Responsibility** — taking ownership of your actions on and off the pitch\n\n**For Players:**\nAlways shake hands before and after a match. Accept referee decisions without argument. Help an injured opponent. Celebrate goals with respect — no taunting.\n\n**For Coaches:**\nModel the behaviour you want to see. Never instruct players to foul deliberately. Praise effort over results. Create a safe, inclusive training environment. The FIFA Fair Play Code states: 'Play to win but accept defeat with dignity.'\n\n**OFA Values in Action:**\nAt Olufunke Football Academy, we believe that how you play defines who you are. Our players are trained to be champions in character first, football second."],

  [3, 'Teamwork & Leadership on the Pitch', 'both', '20 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-people-fill',
   "Great teams are built on communication, trust, and shared purpose.\n\n**The 5 Pillars of Team Cohesion:**\n1. **Communication** — verbal and non-verbal signals, calling for the ball, organising defence\n2. **Trust** — believing in your teammates' decisions and abilities\n3. **Roles & Responsibilities** — every player knows their job\n4. **Collective Goals** — team success over individual glory\n5. **Resilience** — bouncing back together after setbacks\n\n**Leadership Styles in Football:**\n- **Vocal Leader** — organises, motivates, communicates constantly (e.g. goalkeeper, central midfielder)\n- **Lead by Example** — works hardest in training, never gives up (e.g. striker, winger)\n- **Tactical Leader** — reads the game, makes smart decisions under pressure\n\n**For Players — Practical Tips:**\n- Always communicate your position: 'Man on!', 'Turn!', 'Time!'\n- Support teammates after mistakes — never blame\n- Celebrate assists as much as goals\n\n**For Coaches — Building Team Culture:**\n- Rotate the captain role to develop leadership across the squad\n- Use small-sided games to build communication habits\n- Debrief after every match — what did we do well as a TEAM?"],

  [4, 'Nutrition & Recovery for Footballers', 'both', '25 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-heart-pulse-fill',
   "What you eat and how you recover directly impacts your performance on the pitch.\n\n**Pre-Match Nutrition (3-4 hours before):**\n- Complex carbohydrates: rice, pasta, yam, plantain\n- Lean protein: chicken, fish, eggs\n- Avoid: heavy fried foods, excess sugar, fizzy drinks\n- Hydrate: 500ml water 2 hours before kick-off\n\n**During the Match:**\n- Sip water at half-time (200-300ml)\n- Avoid energy drinks — they cause dehydration\n\n**Post-Match Recovery (within 30 minutes):**\n- Protein + carbs: banana + groundnuts, rice + beans\n- Rehydrate: 1.5x the fluid you lost through sweat\n- Stretch for 10-15 minutes\n\n**Sleep — The Most Powerful Recovery Tool:**\n- 8-10 hours for players aged 13-19\n- Sleep is when muscles repair and grow\n- Consistent sleep schedule improves reaction time and decision-making\n\n**For Coaches:**\n- Educate parents on pre-match meal timing\n- Schedule training sessions to allow adequate recovery\n- Monitor players who appear fatigued — rest is training too\n\n**Nigerian Foods That Fuel Performance:**\n- Oats with banana — excellent pre-training breakfast\n- Jollof rice with chicken — ideal pre-match meal\n- Zobo (hibiscus drink) — natural antioxidant for recovery"],

  [5, 'Injury Prevention & First Aid Basics', 'both', '20 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-bandaid-fill',
   "Preventing injuries is as important as developing skills.\n\n**The Warm-Up — FIFA 11+ Protocol:**\nThe FIFA 11+ is a complete warm-up programme proven to reduce injuries by up to 50%.\n\nPhase 1 — Running Exercises (8 minutes):\n- Jogging in a straight line\n- Hip out/in rotation\n- Circling partner\n- Jumping with hip rotation\n- Quick forward/backward runs\n\nPhase 2 — Strength, Plyometrics & Balance (10 minutes):\n- Nordic hamstring curls\n- Single-leg balance\n- Squats\n- Jumping lunges\n\nPhase 3 — Running Exercises (2 minutes):\n- Bounding strides\n- Plant and cut movements\n\n**Most Common Football Injuries:**\n1. Ankle sprains — RICE: Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation\n2. Hamstring strains — stop play immediately, no stretching\n3. Knee injuries (ACL) — requires medical attention\n4. Shin splints — reduce training load, ice after sessions\n5. Head injuries — NEVER return to play same day\n\n**For Coaches — First Aid Essentials:**\n- Always have a first aid kit at training\n- Know the signs of concussion: headache, confusion, dizziness\n- Have emergency contact numbers for all players\n- Never pressure an injured player to continue"],
