// ── TECHNICAL TRAINING COURSE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
$techLessons = [
  [1, 'Ball Mastery & First Touch', 'both', '30 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-circle-fill',
   "Ball mastery is the foundation of all technical ability in football.\n\n**What is Ball Mastery?**\nThe ability to control the ball in any situation — under pressure, at speed, in tight spaces — using all surfaces of the foot.\n\n**Key Surfaces of the Foot:**\n- Inside foot — most accurate for passing and control\n- Outside foot — used for disguised passes and dribbling\n- Sole — used for rolling, shielding, and quick direction changes\n- Instep (laces) — used for shooting and long passes\n- Heel — used for back-heels and flicks\n\n**Ball Mastery Drills (10 minutes daily):**\n1. **Toe Taps** — alternate tapping the top of the ball with each foot, 30 seconds\n2. **Inside-Outside Rolls** — roll ball with inside, then outside of same foot\n3. **V-Pull** — pull ball back with sole, push forward with inside foot\n4. **Scissors** — step over the ball with one foot, push away with the other\n5. **Cruyff Turn** — fake to pass/shoot, drag ball behind standing leg\n\n**First Touch Principles:**\n- Cushion the ball — don't let it bounce away\n- Take the touch away from pressure\n- Set yourself for the next action (pass, shoot, dribble)\n- Use your body as a shield when receiving under pressure\n\n**For Coaches — Session Design:**\nSpend 10-15 minutes of every session on ball mastery. Use music to keep energy high. Progress from stationary to moving to under pressure. The FIFA Technical Activation protocol recommends high-frequency, high-volume repetition for skill acquisition."],

  [2, 'Passing & Receiving', 'both', '30 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-arrow-left-right',
   "Passing is the language of football. Master it and you control the game.\n\n**Types of Passes:**\n1. **Short Pass (Inside Foot)** — most accurate, used in tight spaces\n   - Plant foot beside the ball, toe pointing at target\n   - Strike through the middle of the ball\n   - Follow through toward target\n\n2. **Long Pass (Instep/Laces)** — used to switch play, find forwards\n   - Approach at slight angle\n   - Plant foot 15-20cm beside ball\n   - Strike through bottom half for height\n\n3. **Through Ball** — played into space behind the defence\n   - Weight is critical — too hard = goalkeeper, too soft = offside trap\n   - Disguise your intention before playing it\n\n4. **Back-Heel** — used to surprise opponents\n5. **Chip Pass** — used to play over a pressing defender\n\n**Receiving Principles:**\n- Scan before the ball arrives — know where you'll play next\n- Open your body to receive across the pitch\n- Take your first touch away from pressure\n- Communicate: 'Yes!', 'Turn!', 'Man on!'\n\n**Passing Drills:**\n- **Rondo (4v1, 5v2)** — keep possession in a circle, develop quick passing\n- **Pass and Move** — always move after passing, no standing still\n- **Triangle Passing** — 3 players, 2 touches maximum\n\n**For Coaches:**\nThe rondo is the most effective passing drill in football. Used by Barcelona, Ajax, and all elite academies. Start with 4v1, progress to 5v2, then directional rondos. Key coaching points: weight of pass, angle of support, communication."],

  [3, 'Shooting & Finishing', 'player', '30 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-bullseye',
   "Goals win games. Clinical finishing separates good players from great ones.\n\n**Types of Shots:**\n1. **Instep Drive (Power Shot)**\n   - Approach at 30-45 degree angle\n   - Plant foot beside the ball, toe pointing at goal\n   - Strike through the centre with laces\n   - Follow through — don't stop your leg\n   - Keep head down, eyes on ball at moment of contact\n\n2. **Side-Foot Finish (Placement)**\n   - Used inside the box for accuracy\n   - Strike with inside of foot\n   - Pick your corner — goalkeeper's near post or far post\n\n3. **Volley**\n   - Keep eyes on the ball\n   - Strike through the centre\n   - Lean slightly back for height, forward to keep it down\n\n4. **Header**\n   - Attack the ball — don't wait for it\n   - Use forehead, not top of head\n   - Eyes open, mouth closed\n   - Generate power from neck and upper body\n\n**Finishing Principles:**\n- Shoot early — goalkeepers hate early shots\n- Pick your spot before the ball arrives\n- Stay calm — slow your breathing\n- If in doubt, hit the target\n\n**Shooting Drills:**\n- **1v1 with Goalkeeper** — develop composure in front of goal\n- **Crossing and Finishing** — movement, timing, different angles\n- **Rebound Finishing** — react to parried shots\n\n**For Coaches:**\nCreate shooting drills that replicate match situations. Always include a defender or time pressure. Track goals-to-shots ratio in training to measure improvement."],

  [4, 'Dribbling & 1v1 Skills', 'player', '25 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-lightning-fill',
   "Dribbling is the ability to beat an opponent and create space. It is one of the most exciting skills in football.\n\n**Principles of Effective Dribbling:**\n1. **Keep the ball close** — no more than 1-2 touches ahead\n2. **Use your body** — shoulder drops, head fakes, change of pace\n3. **Protect the ball** — use your body as a shield\n4. **Know when to dribble** — not in your own penalty area\n5. **Have an exit plan** — know where you'll go after beating the defender\n\n**Essential Dribbling Moves:**\n\n**Step Over (Ronaldo Chop)**\n- Step over the ball with one foot\n- Push away with the outside of the other foot\n- Accelerate past the defender\n\n**Elastico (Flip-Flap)**\n- Push ball outside with outside of foot\n- Immediately flick inside with inside of same foot\n- Requires quick feet and close control\n\n**Maradona Turn (360)**\n- Sole roll forward with one foot\n- Drag back with other foot\n- Turn 180 degrees away from defender\n\n**Shoulder Drop**\n- Drop one shoulder to fake direction\n- Push ball the other way\n- Accelerate into space\n\n**1v1 Defending (For Defenders):**\n- Stay on your feet — don't dive in\n- Force the attacker onto their weak foot\n- Delay until support arrives\n- Win the ball when the attacker's touch is heavy\n\n**For Coaches:**\nUse 1v1 corridors to develop dribbling under pressure. Progress from no defender → passive defender → active defender. Reward creativity — let players try new moves without fear of failure."],

  [5, 'Tactical Awareness & Positioning', 'both', '35 mins', 'advanced', 'bi-diagram-3-fill',
   "Understanding the game tactically separates intelligent players from instinctive ones.\n\n**The 4 Phases of the Game:**\n1. **In Possession** — what do we do when we have the ball?\n2. **Out of Possession** — how do we defend as a team?\n3. **Transition to Attack** — winning the ball and going forward quickly\n4. **Transition to Defence** — losing the ball and pressing immediately\n\n**Positional Play Principles:**\n- **Width** — stretch the opposition by using the full width of the pitch\n- **Depth** — create passing options in front and behind the ball\n- **Triangles** — always create triangles of support around the ball carrier\n- **Third Man Runs** — the player who doesn't receive the pass makes a run\n\n**Defensive Organisation:**\n- **Compact shape** — reduce space between lines\n- **Press triggers** — when to press (bad touch, back pass, goalkeeper)\n- **Cover and balance** — one player presses, others cover\n- **Defensive line** — push up to compress space, drop to protect\n\n**Common Formations:**\n- **4-3-3** — attacking, wide, requires high-energy wingers\n- **4-4-2** — balanced, good defensive shape, requires two hard-working strikers\n- **4-2-3-1** — modern, double pivot protects defence, number 10 creates\n- **3-5-2** — wing-backs provide width, strong in midfield\n\n**For Coaches — Session Design:**\nUse positional games (rondos with goals) to teach tactical concepts. Shadow play (no opposition) to rehearse shape and movement. Small-sided games (5v5, 7v7) to apply tactical principles in realistic scenarios.\n\n**OFA Playing Philosophy:**\nOlufunke FA plays a possession-based, high-pressing style. Players are expected to press immediately after losing the ball and build from the back with confidence."],

  [6, 'Set Pieces — Attacking & Defending', 'both', '25 mins', 'advanced', 'bi-flag-fill',
   "Up to 30% of goals in football come from set pieces. Mastering them gives your team a massive advantage.\n\n**Corner Kicks — Attacking:**\n- **Near Post Run** — attacker attacks the near post to flick on\n- **Far Post Run** — attacker attacks the far post for a header\n- **Penalty Spot Run** — attacker arrives late at the penalty spot\n- **Short Corner** — play short to create a crossing angle\n- **Inswinger vs Outswinger** — inswinger causes chaos, outswinger allows attackers to attack the ball\n\n**Corner Kicks — Defending:**\n- Zonal marking: players defend zones, not men\n- Man marking: each defender marks a specific attacker\n- Hybrid: zonal at near post, man-marking at far post\n- Always have a player on each post\n\n**Free Kicks — Attacking:**\n- **Direct Shot** — power and placement over the wall\n- **Dummy Run** — one player runs over the ball, another shoots\n- **Layoff** — short pass to a runner arriving late\n- **Chip over wall** — for free kicks 25-30 yards out\n\n**Free Kicks — Defending:**\n- Wall of 3-5 players, 9.15m from ball\n- Goalkeeper organises the wall\n- One player in wall watches for short free kick\n- Remaining defenders mark runners\n\n**Throw-Ins:**\n- Long throw-in near the box is a dangerous weapon\n- Short throw-in to maintain possession\n- Always have a second option\n\n**For Coaches:**\nDedicate 10-15 minutes per week to set piece rehearsal. Keep routines simple — 2-3 attacking corners, 1-2 free kick routines. Repetition builds confidence and execution."],
];

