// ── SPORTS PSYCHOLOGY COURSE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
$psyLessons = [
  [1, 'The Mental Game — Introduction to Sports Psychology', 'both', '20 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-brain',
   "Elite performance is 50% physical and 50% mental. Sports psychology gives you the tools to unlock your full potential.\n\n**What is Sports Psychology?**\nSports psychology is the study of how psychological factors affect performance and how participation in sport affects psychological and physical factors.\n\n**The 5 Core Mental Skills:**\n1. **Confidence** — believing in your ability to succeed\n2. **Focus** — directing attention to what matters most\n3. **Motivation** — the drive to train hard and compete\n4. **Emotional Control** — managing anxiety, frustration, and pressure\n5. **Resilience** — bouncing back from setbacks and mistakes\n\n**The Performance Zone:**\nEvery player has an optimal arousal level for peak performance. Too relaxed = underperformance. Too anxious = overperformance. Finding your zone is the goal.\n\n**For Players:**\nThink about your best ever performance. How did you feel? Confident? Relaxed? Focused? That was your performance zone. Sports psychology helps you get there consistently.\n\n**For Coaches:**\nUnderstanding your players' mental states is as important as understanding their technical ability. A player who is anxious, distracted, or low in confidence will underperform regardless of their physical ability.\n\n**OFA Mental Performance Commitment:**\nAt Olufunke Football Academy, we develop the whole player — mind, body, and character. Mental skills training is integrated into every training session."],

  [2, 'Building Confidence & Self-Belief', 'both', '25 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-star-fill',
   "Confidence is not something you either have or don't have — it is a skill you can build.\n\n**What is Confidence in Football?**\nThe belief that you can execute a skill, make a decision, or perform under pressure successfully.\n\n**Sources of Confidence:**\n1. **Past Performance** — remembering your best moments\n2. **Preparation** — knowing you've trained hard\n3. **Physical State** — feeling fit, strong, and ready\n4. **Social Support** — encouragement from coaches, teammates, family\n5. **Self-Talk** — what you say to yourself\n\n**Positive Self-Talk Techniques:**\n- Replace 'I can't' with 'I will'\n- Replace 'I always miss penalties' with 'I've scored penalties before and I will again'\n- Use cue words: 'Strong', 'Sharp', 'Calm', 'Ready'\n- Pre-match affirmations: 'I am prepared. I am capable. I will compete.'\n\n**The Confidence Cycle:**\nPreparation → Performance → Success → Confidence → Better Preparation\n\n**For Players — Confidence Builders:**\n- Keep a 'highlight reel' in your mind of your best moments\n- Set small, achievable goals in training\n- Celebrate small wins — a good first touch, a successful tackle\n- Don't compare yourself to others — compare yourself to yesterday's version of you\n\n**For Coaches — Building Player Confidence:**\n- Praise effort and process, not just results\n- Give players roles that match their current ability level\n- Create training environments where mistakes are learning opportunities\n- Use the 'sandwich' feedback method: positive → improvement → positive"],

  [3, 'Focus & Concentration Under Pressure', 'both', '25 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-eye-fill',
   "The ability to focus under pressure is what separates good players from great ones.\n\n**Types of Focus in Football:**\n1. **Broad External** — scanning the whole pitch, reading the game\n2. **Narrow External** — focusing on the ball, a specific opponent\n3. **Broad Internal** — thinking about tactics, game plan\n4. **Narrow Internal** — focusing on your breathing, body sensations\n\n**Common Focus Disruptors:**\n- Crowd noise and abuse\n- Referee decisions\n- Mistakes (your own or teammates')\n- Score line\n- Fatigue\n- Negative self-talk\n\n**Refocusing Techniques:**\n\n**The 3R Process:**\n1. **Recognise** — notice you've lost focus\n2. **Release** — let go of the distraction (deep breath, physical cue)\n3. **Refocus** — return attention to the next action\n\n**Physical Cues:**\n- Clap your hands once to reset\n- Touch your wristband or captain's armband\n- Take a deep breath and exhale slowly\n- Look at the ball — the ball is always in the present moment\n\n**Pre-Performance Routines:**\nElite players use consistent routines before penalties, free kicks, and throw-ins to trigger focus. Develop your own routine: 3 deep breaths, visualise the action, execute.\n\n**For Coaches:**\nCreate training environments with distractions (noise, pressure, consequences) to build focus under pressure. Debrief players on their focus after matches — not just their physical performance."],

  [4, 'Managing Anxiety & Pre-Match Nerves', 'both', '20 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-heart-fill',
   "Nerves are normal. Every elite athlete experiences them. The key is using them as fuel, not letting them become fear.\n\n**Understanding Anxiety in Sport:**\nAnxiety is your body's natural response to a perceived threat or challenge. In football, it manifests as:\n- Butterflies in the stomach\n- Increased heart rate\n- Sweaty palms\n- Negative thoughts ('What if I miss?')\n- Muscle tension\n\n**Reframing Anxiety:**\nResearch shows that telling yourself 'I am excited' rather than 'I am nervous' improves performance. Both states feel similar physically — the difference is your interpretation.\n\n**Breathing Techniques:**\n\n**Box Breathing (4-4-4-4):**\n1. Inhale for 4 counts\n2. Hold for 4 counts\n3. Exhale for 4 counts\n4. Hold for 4 counts\nRepeat 4 times. This activates the parasympathetic nervous system and reduces anxiety.\n\n**Progressive Muscle Relaxation:**\nTense each muscle group for 5 seconds, then release. Start from feet, work up to face. Releases physical tension before matches.\n\n**Pre-Match Routine for Players:**\n- Arrive early — rushing increases anxiety\n- Warm up properly — physical activity reduces anxiety\n- Listen to your favourite music\n- Use positive self-talk\n- Focus on what you can control (your effort, your attitude)\n\n**For Coaches:**\nCreate a calm, positive pre-match environment. Avoid overloading players with tactical information in the final minutes. Use humour to reduce tension. Remind players of their preparation and capability."],

  [5, 'Resilience — Bouncing Back from Setbacks', 'both', '25 mins', 'intermediate', 'bi-arrow-repeat',
   "Every footballer faces setbacks — missed penalties, bad form, injuries, defeats. Resilience is what keeps you going.\n\n**What is Resilience?**\nThe ability to adapt positively in the face of adversity, trauma, tragedy, threats, or significant sources of stress.\n\n**The 4 Components of Resilience:**\n1. **Emotional Regulation** — managing your emotional response to setbacks\n2. **Optimism** — believing things will improve\n3. **Self-Efficacy** — confidence in your ability to overcome challenges\n4. **Social Support** — leaning on teammates, coaches, family\n\n**The Resilience Response Model:**\nSetback → Emotional Response → Reflection → Learning → Growth\n\n**For Players — After a Bad Game:**\n- Allow yourself 24 hours to feel disappointed — it's healthy\n- After 24 hours, shift to learning mode: What can I improve?\n- Write down 3 things you did well and 1 thing to work on\n- Return to training with renewed purpose\n- Remember: Every elite player has had bad games. Messi missed penalties. Ronaldo had poor seasons.\n\n**For Players — After an Injury:**\n- Focus on what you CAN do, not what you can't\n- Use recovery time to study the game, improve mentally\n- Set small daily goals for rehabilitation\n- Stay connected to the team\n\n**For Coaches — Building Resilient Players:**\n- Create training environments where failure is safe\n- Debrief after defeats — focus on learning, not blame\n- Share stories of elite players who overcame adversity\n- Develop a 'growth mindset' culture: ability is developed through effort\n\n**OFA Resilience Mantra:**\n'We fall, we learn, we rise. Every setback is a setup for a comeback.'"],

  [6, 'Goal Setting & Motivation', 'both', '20 mins', 'beginner', 'bi-trophy-fill',
   "Clear goals give you direction, purpose, and the motivation to keep working when it gets hard.\n\n**The SMART Goal Framework:**\n- **S**pecific — exactly what do you want to achieve?\n- **M**easurable — how will you know when you've achieved it?\n- **A**chievable — is it realistic given your current level?\n- **R**elevant — does it align with your bigger football goals?\n- **T**ime-bound — when will you achieve it?\n\n**Example SMART Goals:**\n\nPlayer: 'I will improve my weak foot by practising 50 passes with my left foot every day for the next 4 weeks.'\n\nCoach: 'I will complete the CAF C Coaching Licence by December 2026 by studying 3 hours per week.'\n\n**Types of Goals:**\n1. **Outcome Goals** — winning the league, scoring 10 goals (motivating but not fully in your control)\n2. **Performance Goals** — completing 80% of passes, winning 60% of headers (measurable, in your control)\n3. **Process Goals** — scanning before receiving, pressing within 3 seconds of losing the ball (daily habits)\n\n**The Goal Ladder:**\nLong-term dream → Medium-term goals → Short-term weekly goals → Daily habits\n\n**Motivation Types:**\n- **Intrinsic** — playing because you love it (most powerful, most sustainable)\n- **Extrinsic** — playing for rewards, recognition (useful short-term)\n\n**For Coaches:**\nSet individual goals with each player at the start of the season. Review monthly. Celebrate progress, not just achievement. Help players connect their daily training to their long-term dreams.\n\n**OFA Goal-Setting Session:**\nEvery OFA player sets 3 goals at the start of each season: 1 technical, 1 physical, 1 personal development goal. These are reviewed monthly with their coach."],

  [7, 'Mindfulness & Visualisation for Peak Performance', 'both', '25 mins', 'advanced', 'bi-eye',
   "The world's best footballers use visualisation and mindfulness to prepare mentally for peak performance.\n\n**What is Visualisation?**\nCreating a vivid mental image of successfully performing a skill or action before you physically do it. Used by Cristiano Ronaldo, Lionel Messi, and virtually every elite athlete.\n\n**How to Visualise Effectively:**\n1. Find a quiet space, close your eyes\n2. Take 5 deep breaths to relax\n3. Picture yourself in the specific situation (penalty kick, 1v1, corner kick)\n4. See it in first person — through your own eyes\n5. Include all senses: see the goal, hear the crowd, feel the ball\n6. Visualise the perfect execution — the ball hitting the net\n7. Feel the emotion of success\n8. Repeat 3-5 times\n\n**Visualisation for Different Situations:**\n- **Before a penalty** — see your run-up, your contact, the ball in the net\n- **Before a match** — see yourself making key tackles, passes, runs\n- **During injury recovery** — visualise the injured area healing, yourself returning to play\n\n**Mindfulness in Football:**\nMindfulness is the practice of being fully present in the current moment — not thinking about the last mistake or the next match, but fully engaged in what is happening right now.\n\n**Simple Mindfulness Practice:**\n- Before training, take 2 minutes to focus only on your breathing\n- During training, notice the feel of the ball, the sound of your boots\n- After training, reflect on 3 things you did well\n\n**For Coaches:**\nIntroduce 2-minute mindfulness breathing at the start of training sessions. Use visualisation as part of set-piece preparation. Encourage players to develop pre-performance routines."],
];

